Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @sweet potatoes{2} into ¼-inch-thick wedges. Toss sweet potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%oz} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Swap in broccoli for sweet potatoes; roast, ~{15-18%minutes}. (Save sweet potatoes for another use.)

Meanwhile, trim @scallions{2} and cut greens into 1-inch pieces; mince whites. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Halve @potato buns{2}. Slice @mini cucumber{1} into ¼-inch-thick rounds.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}, 1 tsp @soy sauce{2%tablespoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings), ¼ tsp @sugar{1/4%tsp} (½ tsp for 4), and @sriracha{1%tsp} to taste. (Be sure to measure the soy sauce—we sent more.)

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{5%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add scallion greens and cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly charred and fragrant, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Add garlic and cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute} more.

Turn off heat; transfer scallion mixture (including oil!) to a large #bowl{} and season with salt and pepper. Wipe out pan.

In a second large bowl, combine @ground beef{10%oz}, scallion whites, and half the @fry seasoning{1%tablespoon} (all for 4 servings). Form into two patties (four patties for 4), each slightly larger than a burger bun. Season generously with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for scallions over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

While patties cook, toast buns until golden brown.

Transfer sweet potatoes to bowl with scallion mixture; toss to combine. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Toss broccoli with scallion mixture; season as instructed.

Spread cut sides of bottom buns with as much sauce as you like. Fill buns with patties, cucumber, and more sauce if desired. Serve with sweet potatoes and any remaining sauce on the side for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.